  "beats": [
    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "This is Liam, in for Bear. Two quantum waves can have exactly the same probability density while carrying motion in opposite directions. The missing direction is stored in complex phase.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "remotion",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "provenance": "proven-core/ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "command": "How can two wave functions have the same |psi|^2 but move in opposite directions?",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS — COMPLEX PHASE",
            "segment": "The Hidden Arrow of Motion",
            "greeting": "Hallo, Liam",
            "runningText": "comparing equal densities and opposite currents…",
            "output": [
              "Magnitude gives probability.",
              "Phase gradient gives direction."
            ],
            "folderLabel": "@NikBearBrown",
            "modelLabel": "Fable 5",
            "effortLabel": "High"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B01.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.88,
      "build": {
        "status": "VIDEO",
        "src": "media/B01.mp4",
        "filled_by": "media",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:32:25"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Take a right-moving plane wave e to the i k x and a left-moving one e to the minus i k x. Their real and imaginary parts wind around the complex plane in opposite senses.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.14,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:32:25"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "estimated_duration_s": 6,
      "narration_text": "If their measured position probabilities are identical, where does left versus right live?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 5.57,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:32:25"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Square the magnitude of either wave. Both give one everywhere. The density erases the sign of k and cannot identify the direction.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "cancel"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.26,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:32:25"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Now plot each complex amplitude as an arrow while x increases. For positive k, the phase angle advances. For negative k, it retreats.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "rotate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.02,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:32:25"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "That spatial twist is the phase gradient. Write psi as R e to the i theta. The density is R squared, while the gradient of theta carries the directional information.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "derive"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.18,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:32:25"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "The probability current makes this explicit: j equals h bar over m times the imaginary part of psi star times d psi by d x. For e to plus i k x, j is positive. For e to minus i k x, j is negative.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "split"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 14.4,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:32:25"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Keep only a real cosine and the current vanishes. It is an equal superposition of right and left momentum, a standing pattern rather than one directed plane wave.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "merge"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.96,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:32:25"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "So the imaginary part is not decorative. Together with the real part, it lets the state encode a continuous phase angle and a nonzero probability flow.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "map"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.69,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:32:25"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "A localized packet works the same way. Two packets can share the same Gaussian envelope at one instant while opposite phase ramps give opposite mean momenta.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.39,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:32:25"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Careful: a wave function can be real at one chosen instant. The point is that a general state and its time evolution require complex amplitudes to preserve phase and direction.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "qualify"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.75,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B11.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:32:25"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "Magnitude answers where. Complex phase answers how the probability flows. Lose the phase, and left and right collapse into the same incomplete picture.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.17,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B12.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:32:25"
      }
    },
    {
